HIV/AIDS, non-communicable diseases in eight key areas.
GENÈVE - Non-communicable diseases (NCD), such as heart disease, stroke, cancer, diabetes, and chronic lung diseases, are responsible for 70% of all deaths.
There is irrefutable evidence that the use of tobacco, sedentary behavior, poor diet, and excessive alcohol consumption increase the chances of prematurely dying from non-communicable diseases.
Despite a wide knowledge of the risks, global obesity is generally not controlled, while tobacco and alcohol consumption continue to rise.
It was within this context that non-communicable disease alliance networks came together from December 9 to 11 at the second Global Alliance on Non-Communicable Diseases Forum in the United Arab Emirates.
In their search for solutions aimed at regulating MNTs, they should draw inspiration from the fight against AIDS.
People living with and affected by HIV continue to lead interventions and their unique form of mobilization has been essential in the progress made.
While the battle is not over, AIDS activists know they can win this battle.
In the same way, a mobilization movement against MNTs can slow down this epidemic.
However, in 2015, Richard Horton, the editor-in-chief of The Lancet, described the NMD community as awaiting 'a jolt for its semi-comatose mind.' He added: 'But who will have the courage to administer it?'
We believe that there are lessons to be learned from AIDS activists.
As the world's attention focuses on malaria prevention, those seeking to master preventable diseases must draw inspiration from the ABC of AIDS activist organizations.
The first letter the MNT community should take into account is 'A', as activism.
Everyone over 40 certainly remembers the images of AIDS activists participating in "die-in" demonstrations at scientific conferences all around the world.
In the United States, AIDS activists took to the streets, even shutting down the headquarters of the Food and Drug Administration for a day in October 1988.
At the global level, activists have put pressure on governments and pharmaceutical companies to make medicines more affordable.
This activism continues and should serve as a model for action on non-communicable diseases.
Then, the MNT Community must adopt a more daring approach to budgets - the 'B' of the movement's anti-AIDS strategy.
Civil civic organization and grassroots activism can initially galvanize energies, but the organization and maintenance of a broad coalition requires money.
The fight against AIDS movement was clear on this issue from the start and put pressure to obtain resources to support its awareness and accountability activities effectively.
"C" represents coalitions: the movements fighting against AIDS soon realized that progress comes only with multiple support.
The activists established links between people living with HIV and those who have other concerns, such as women's rights, intellectual property rights, nutrition, and housing.
Coalitions and specialized campaigns work better when they bring together internal and external leaders from the public sector, in order to combine their perspectives and expertise.
The fight against AIDS movement also understood that a global response to the epidemic is essential to the spread of its support.
So, "D", the determining factor of success, has consisted of 'drawing attention to the interconnectedness of the challenge.'
For instance, lobbying education leaders to keep girls in school longer has contributed to providing young people with knowledge and the power to make informed decisions about the timing and person with whom to negotiate protected sexual relationships.
Similarly, links have been established between groups working on poverty, gender equality, and nutrition: all factors that played a key role in the AIDS crisis.
The MNTs are not less isolated in their causality and are also the subject of a multisectoral approach to prevention.
The commitment - "E" - was what helped the AIDS movement to gain such great influence.
Through strategic borrowings from the disability rights movement, which defended the key phrase "Nothing about us without us," advocates for the AIDS cause demanded representation from existing organizations to address the disease.
For example, UNAIDS remains the only United Nations agency with seats on its Board of directors for civil society representatives.
This standard is so strongly integrated into the movement to fight AIDS that it would be almost unthinkable for an AIDS meeting to take place without representation from the community.
Preventive disease movements must also develop convincing stories and the "F" - the question formulation - is essential for the AIDS community to obtain the support of political leaders.
In particular, access to treatments against AIDS was presented as a question of economic justice.
Narrating the story in this way leads to a significant reduction in the price of medicines, to such an extent that more than half of the people living with HIV in low- and middle-income countries are on treatment.
A formulation just as important for the question of AIDS, a question very relevant to the MNT movement, is that of responsibility.
The HIV community worked hard to put more emphasis on individuals' life choices, rather than attributing state responsibility for healthcare provision and the eradication of legal discrimination.
In the debate on AIDS, the gender - the "G" of our movement - has been a significant point.
HIV was initially considered a "gay disease" and the gender identity was rooted from the start in the DNA of the AIDS activism movement.
The gender dimensions of these diseases are no less significant: it's enough to look at how alcohol and tobacco are marketed to understand it.
The genre, as a result, should become a focal point for MNT prevention efforts.
Finally, "H" - human rights - are the foundation for the response to AIDS.
Campaigns have been launched against workplace discrimination, in schools, and in medical centers.
The strategic dispute allowed for equality under the law.
The HIV/AIDS activist movement refused to hold major conferences in countries with repressive laws against people living with HIV.
The MNT movement might adopt the same strategy, for example, by refusing to meet in countries that fail to limit unhealthy food advertising to children.
We might continue down the alphabet with a list of lessons learned from the fight against AIDS, but it seems fitting to close on 'H', given that human rights have provided the answer to AIDS and should provide the answer to non-communicable diseases.
Poverty, exclusion, as well as social and economic marginalization put people at greater risk of HIV.
It is the same for the MNT.
The initial reaction to the AIDS epidemic was to wonder: "Why don't these people make better choices?" The AIDS activist movement made it clear that this question is not the right one.
Today, with 70% of the planet in peril of premature death due to preventable diseases, "these people" represent a large number of us.
Communities of MNT and HIV/AIDS may learn from each other.
We are a stronger movement when we unite our forces.
The opinions expressed here do not necessarily reflect those of UNAIDS.
